      "message": "\u003e So it\u0027s wrong to re-use our own code?\n\nYou\u0027re taking something said in the context of this specific line of code, and claiming I said it was some general rule.  In this specific context, I believe that not relying on the existing content is a good thing (to avoid the threadpool).\n\n\u003e \n\u003e You can still run the script if you import code from another python file. It\u0027s a common feature in python.\n\nTrue, but now I have to maintain dependencies cross script, as as stated elsewhere, I\u0027m not at the point where I want to maintain this as anything other than one isolated test.\n\nIf we get to what you talk about elsewhere, where we have the \"real\" parser runnable as a c++ app, I agree, it makes sense to consolidate.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e \u003e I\u0027m not worried about this minor amount of code duplication in a CI script.\n\u003e \n\u003e I think you are taking too many shortcuts here. Whatever you merge will potentially stay in the repo for a long time and all contributors will have to work with it or work around it.\n\nAbsolutely right, I am taking shortcuts because I\u0027m spending too much time reviewing incorrect patches and I need automation.  If you\u0027re interested in helping to refactor these things in the way you envision, I could really use the help.  I\u0027m not against a lot of your ideas, just that I don\u0027t have time for it.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e \n\u003e If is acceptable then what prevents us from duplicating 100-line functions?\n\nThis is not duplicating 100 line functions, but to answer your question: Maintainers.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e Or copy-pasting entire applications like how it was done in dbus-sensors?\n\nI\u0027m not going to debate the history of how dbus-sensors came to be in a single code review.  If you\u0027re interested, I\u0027m happy to walk you through how that was allowed (hint, the maintainer wanted to support people merging code).  Ultimately what\u0027s there is now what the majority of people use, versus alternatives that enforced a lot more rules and were \"cleaner\" in design.  If you want to use those, I believe they\u0027re still available.",
